    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. so if mechanical tension is the main thing for growth, how does the body actually translate that physical force into a signaling process at the cellular level? like what's happening inside the fiber?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you apply mechanical tension, you are essentially creating microscopic tears in the muscle fibers, which is the crucial first step. These tears are not just damage; they are signals. The muscle cells, or myocytes, sense this physical strain and initiate a cascade of events inside the cell.\n\nThis signaling process involves things like the activation of signaling molecules, most notably the mTOR pathway. mTOR is the master switch, and when mechanical tension is high, it gets flipped on, telling the cell, \"Hey, we need to build more protein and repair this damage!\" This is how the cell translates the external force into an internal command for hypertrophy.",
      "source": "target",
